30|$|As part of {{its effort}} to protect workers from job loss, Sri Lanka adopted the Termination of Employment of Workman Act (TEWA) in 1971. The act aimed to limit {{unemployment}} by raising the cost of layoffs. It required that each layoff of a covered worker, whether the layoff involved a single employee or a mass layoff, {{must be approved by}} the government. Until 2003, the government also determined on a case-by-case basis the level of severance pay that the firm was required to pay to the <b>laid</b> <b>off</b> <b>workers.</b>|$|R
